IAT432 Project: YouTube Creator Studio Usability Study

This study aimed to assess and enhance the YouTube Creator Studio usability for diverse users. The focus was on identifying interaction, navigation, and cognitive issues in managing content, especially for frequent and casual YouTubers.

Project 1.1: Planning & Preparing the Test

Initial planning included setting participant goals and designing tasks to reflect typical actions such as video uploading, metadata management, analytics, playlist creation, and captioning. We made detailed task instructions like uploading a titled video “Test Video by Participant [#]” to reduce ambiguity and ensure clear guidance.

Participants

A diverse set of participants, including frequent YouTubers and casual users, ensured varied insights. This diversity addressed usability across experience levels, focusing on different user goals and interactions.

Study Goals and Task Design

The usability tasks included:

  • Upload a Video: Measure comfort in uploading, scheduling, and metadata understanding.
  • Closed Captioning: Evaluate ease of adding and syncing captions using tools like auto-sync.
  • Copyright Review: Identify navigation and understanding of copyright management.
  • Analyze Performance: Test metrics interpretation in analytics.
  • Download Reports: Assess report export ability for offline review.

Observations and Findings

  • Cognitive Overload: Users felt overwhelmed by analytics data.
  • Ambiguous Terminology: Terms like "traffic source" confused casual users.
  • Feature Discoverability Issues: Navigation challenges due to interface layers.

Prototyping Solutions - Project 1.4

The prototype addressed cognitive load and learnability issues with redesigned analytics and subtitle editing:

  • Guided Workflow for Subtitling: Step-by-step process with icons and descriptions for better understanding.
  • Key Metrics Highlighted: Simplified analytics layout prioritizing essential metrics.
  • Tooltips for Clarity: Hoverable definitions helped with complex terms.

Controlled Studies - Project 3

The study's hypothesis tested if the step-by-step Subtitle Editor could reduce errors. Participants used both the original and redesigned interfaces to gauge improvements in intuitiveness.

Methodology

  • Participants: 26 YouTube users split between original and prototype versions.
  • Hypothesis: Structured subtitling reduces errors, enhancing task completion.
  • Testing Environment: Virtual and in-person settings with real-time observation.

Data Collection

Pre-test and post-test questionnaires, observational tracking, and statistical analysis compared errors, ease-of-use, and hint reliance across both interfaces.

Results

Key findings included a notable reduction in hint requests and improved ease-of-use ratings in the prototype, supporting the hypothesis that guided task flows benefit user navigation.

Conclusion & Recommendations

  • Sequential Workflow: Supports users with a structured task breakdown.
  • Enhanced Tooltips: Reduces confusion with intuitive definitions and interface elements.
  • Onboarding Options: Guides for new users to ease into complex tasks.

Future Enhancements

Additional refinements are suggested to improve interactive feedback and visual clarity further, ensuring elements are unmistakably interactive to streamline user experience across skill levels.
